			<div class='comment'>
				<h3 class='comment-date'>Submitted 04/16/2013</h3>
				<div class='comment-main'>
					<div class='comment-content'><p>I have been involved in the health care quality arena for over 15 years and have seen numerous quality trends come and go. I personally have found the Lean approach is very effective for three simple reasons.</p>
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal;">
    <li>Lean, when done correctly, empowers all staff and, especially those on the front line to identify and fix problems that negatively impacts the patient and themselves at the source. (Imagine an organization where it is every employees job to identify and fix problems.) </li>
    <li>Lean provides structures for process and problem solving to ferret out the root causes to develop robust action plans to address many of the root causes. </li>
    <li>The use of ongoing auditing to assure that the action plans actually improve the problems identified and to assure that the changes stick. </li>
</ol>
<p>On the projects that I have been involved in, I have found that the projects that failed are the ones that did not have any buy in from the staff involved and lack of auditing to assure sustained improvement. The projects that excelled were those that have ongoing metrics and teams composed of the front line staff (subject matter experts) who have a vested interest in the project. One of the other things that can make or break Lean in an organization is management. Management in a Lean environment is very different. Managers need to be supportive of the front line staff identifying both the problems and the solutions. No longer does management come in and dictate what is done and how. Another challenge for management is making time for the front line staff to work on the problems identified.</p></div>
					<p class='comment-author'>Gretchen Davenport, RN, BSN, MBA/HCM, CPHQ</p>
						<p class='comment-position'>Central Lean Coach</p>
										<p class='comment-disclosure'><span class='comment-disclosure-label'>Disclosure/Conflict of Interest:</span> No potential conflicts of interest with respect to this expert commentary.</p>
				</div><!--/.comment-main -->
			</div><!--/.comment -->
			<div class='comment'>
				<h3 class='comment-date'>Submitted 06/20/2011</h3>
